   MT=151 Resolved resonances                                     2634 1451
     The evaluation in the resonance region in based on the       2634 1451
     version of the Atlas that was still in development at the    2634 1451
     time our work was performed [3].  The compilation in the     2634 1451
     Atlas appeared to use parameters generated in Reich-Moore    2634 1451
     approximation. Because the Atlas also contained resonance    2634 1451
     parameters for resonances in the first (n,n) state, we       2634 1451
     decided to convert the Atlas compilation to the LRF=7        2634 1451
     format using Reich-Moore approximation, including the        2634 1451
     first inelastic state.  The change from MLBW Atlas           2634 1451
     parameters to LRF=7 parameters necessitated a refitting      2634 1451
     of the bound levels and R-prime. This change did improve     2634 1451
     agreement between the evaluation and experiment in the       2634 1451
     minima between resonances. The capture widths were known     2634 1451
     only from the area under each resonance. Additionally we     2634 1451
     added several resonances at the upper end of the RRR to      2634 1451
     improve agreement of the RRR with data in the region of      2634 1451
     140-165 keV.  The (n,n) resonances were determined by        2634 1451
     identifying capture resonances with no elastic               2634 1451
     counterpart and subtracting the capture width from the       2634 1451
     total width determined from (n,tot) measurements. The        2634 1451
     (n,n) resonances were assumed to be s-wave only.  This       2634 1451
     choice was supported by the experimental results of Ref.     2634 1451
     [1] and Ref. [2].                                            2634 1451
     Our thermal cross section and computed resonance integral    2634 1451
     values are in excellent agreement with the Atlas             2634 1451
     recommendations [3], as shown in the table below.  Our       2634 1451
     MACS(30 keV) value lies roughly in between the JENDL-4.0     2634 1451
     and KADoNiS-0.3 values and is generally consistent with      2634 1451
     the experimental averaged value given in the new Atlas.      2634 1451
     The Atlas value derived from systematics is more             2634 1451
     consistent with the KADoNiS-0.3 value. We note that the      2634 1451
     in-development version of KADoNiS-1.0 recommends a value     2634 1451
     basically taken from the Giubrone thesis [4], measured       2634 1451
     at CERN n-TOF. This measurement does not span the whole      2634 1451
     energy range of the resonance region. Therefore Giubrone     2634 1451
     omits several low energy resonances that would have          2634 1451
     provided a smooth background to the 30 keV region,           2634 1451
     lowering the MACS(30 keV) value obtained from the            2634 1451
     consideration of that set alone. Thus we use the MACS        2634 1451
     data for validation purposes only.                           2634 1451
