 REACTION MODELING IN FAST NEUTRON RANGE                          2634 1451
 ---------------------------------------                          2634 1451
 The fast region calculations were performed using the EMPIRE     2634 1451
 code, which is a comprehensive package that integrates into a    2634 1451
 single system a number of important physical modules and         2634 1451
 evaluation tools. We have adopted coupled channel (CC)           2634 1451
 calculations in the incident channel and for the direct          2634 1451
 inelastic scattering to collective levels. In addition, we       2634 1451
 have allowed for the Distorted Wave Born Approximation (DWBA)    2634 1451
 to populate presumably collective levels which are not           2634 1451
 included in the ground state band used in the CC calculations    2634 1451
 to adjust neutron emission spectra in the high energy range.     2634 1451
 For the preequilibrium (PE) emission employed the classical      2634 1451
 exciton model (PCROSS module) because of its higher              2634 1451
 flexibility in modeling neutron spectra compared with the        2634 1451
 physically more advanced, but also more rigid quantum            2634 1451
 mechanical models. The same module was also used for the PE      2634 1451
 emission of protons and gammas as well as for PE emission of     2634 1451
 clusters, the latter taking advantage of the Iwamoto-Harada      2634 1451
 model.                                                           2634 1451
 The Hauser-Feshbach formulation of the statistical model was     2634 1451
 employed to follow sequential emission of particles from the     2634 1451
 compound nucleus (CN). The elastic and inelastic angular         2634 1451
 distributions of neutrons emitted from the CN were calculated    2634 1451
 using the Blatt-Biedenharn formalism. The width fluctuation      2634 1451
 factor was accounted for within HRTW formalism applied up to     2634 1451
 12.0 MeV incident neutrons. Compound nucleus and direct cross    2634 1451
 sections were added incoherently.                                2634 1451
 Gilbert-Cameron model for level-density has been adopted         2634 1451
 for all nuclei involved in this evaluation. The parameters were  2634 1451
 fitted to reproduce the asymptotic behavior of discrete          2634 1451
 levels, as well as to correctly describe the observed cross      2634 1451
 sections.                                                        2634 1451
 Complete g-ray cascades for every excited nucleus were           2634 1451
 calculated using M1, E1 and E2 electromagnetic transitions.      2634 1451
 g-strength functions for E1 transitions from the RIPL3 MLO1      2634 1451
 formulation by Pluyko.                                           2634 1451
 Occasionally, we resorted to energy-dependent parameter          2634 1451
 scaling or tuning factors, available in the EMPIRE code, to      2634 1451
 account for model deficiencies. These corrections were           2634 1451
 typically on the level of 1-2% or less and can be found in the   2634 1451
 input files. Whenever possible the reaction model parameters     2634 1451
 used in the 57Fe evaluation were kept consistent with those      2634 1451
 used in the 56Fe evaluation.                                     2634 1451
